Example fails as it appears (in my browser) above. Adding Dictionary in angle brackets and empty square brackets as mentioned by Marko allows it to work without throwing an exception. Final statement looks like

var dic = jss.Deserialize(Dictionary(string,Object)())(json);

where I've sub'd parentheses for angle and square brackets that seem to be getting consumed by the blog system or the browser along the way. You'll figure out which go where :-).

Try this:

<pre>
var json = "[{\"id\":\"588\",\"value\":false},{\"id\":\"486\",\"value\":false}]";
var jss = new JavaScriptSerializer();
var dic = jss.Deserialize(json);
Console.WriteLine(dic[0]["id"]);
</pre>

Works just fine... does it not for you?

Hi, your solution helped me a lot..I just have one thing to add, example where you are using

var dict = jss.Deserialize&lt;Dictionary&gt;(jsonText);

needs to be changed to:

var dict = jss.Deserialize&lt;Dictionary[]&gt;(jsonText);

cheers
